# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-mesh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-mesh/data-catalog] A **database catalog** of a database instance consists of metadata in which definitions of database objects such as base tables, views (virtual tables), synonyms, value ranges, indexes, users, and user groups are stored.
[src:data-mesh/data-catalog] It is an architecture product that documents the database's content and data quality.
[src:data-mesh/data-catalog] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the INFORMATION_SCHEMA, but not all databases follow this, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:data-mesh/data-catalog] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Around the 1970s/1980s the term *information engineering methodology* (IEM) was created to describe database design and the use of software for data analysis and processing.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] These techniques were intended to be used by database administrators (DBAs) and by systems analysts based upon an understanding of the operational processing needs of organizations for the 1980s.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] In particular, these techniques were meant to help bridge the gap between strategic business planning and information systems.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] A key early contributor (often called the "father" of information engineering methodology) was the Australian Clive Finkelstein, who wrote several articles about it between 1976 and 1980, and also co-authored an influential Savant Institute report on it with James Martin.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Over the next few years, Finkelstein continued work in a more business-driven direction, which was intended to address a rapidly changing business environment; Martin continued work in a more data processing-driven direction.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Richter, guided by Clive Finkelstein, played a significant role in revamping IEM as well as helping to design the IEM software product (user data), which helped automate IEM.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] In the early 2000s, the data and data tooling was generally held by the information technology (IT) teams in most companies.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Other teams then used data for their work (e.g. reporting), and there was usually little overlap in data skillset between these parts of the business.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] In the early 2010s, with the rise of the internet, the massive increase in data volumes, velocity, and variety led to the term big data to describe the data itself, and data-driven tech companies like Facebook and Airbnb started using the phrase **data engineer**.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Due to the new scale of the data, major firms like Google, Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, and Netflix started to move away from traditional ETL and storage techniques.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] They started creating **data engineering**, a type of software engineering focused on data, and in particular infrastructure, warehousing, data protection, cybersecurity, mining, modelling, processing, and metadata management.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] This change in approach was particularly focused on cloud computing.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Data started to be handled and used by many parts of the business, such as sales and marketing, and not just IT.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] High-performance computing is critical for the processing and analysis of data.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] One particularly widespread approach to computing for data engineering is dataflow programming, in which the computation is represented as a directed graph (dataflow graph); nodes are the operations, and edges represent the flow of data.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Popular implementations include Apache Spark, and the deep learning specific TensorFlow.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] More recent implementations, such as Differential/Timely Dataflow, have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Data is stored in a variety of ways, one of the key deciding factors is in how the data will be used.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Data engineers optimize data storage and processing systems to reduce costs.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] They use data compression, partitioning, and archiving.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] If the data is structured and some form of online transaction processing is required, then databases are generally used.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Originally mostly relational databases were used, with strong ACID transaction correctness guarantees; most relational databases use SQL for their queries.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] However, with the growth of data in the 2010s, NoSQL databases have also become popular since they horizontally scaled more easily than relational databases by giving up the ACID transaction guarantees, as well as reducing the object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] More recently, NewSQL databases — which attempt to allow horizontal scaling while retaining ACID guarantees — have become popular.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] If the data is structured and online analytical processing is required (but not online transaction processing), then data warehouses are a main choice.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] They enable data analysis, mining, and artificial intelligence on a much larger scale than databases can allow, and indeed data often flow from databases into data warehouses.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Business analysts, data engineers, and data scientists can access data warehouses using tools such as SQL or business intelligence software.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] A data lake is a centralized repository for storing, processing, and securing large volumes of data.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] A data lake can contain structured data from relational databases, semi-structured data, unstructured data, and binary data.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] A data lake can be created on premises or in a cloud-based environment using the services from public cloud vendors such as Amazon, Microsoft, or Google.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] If the data is less structured, then often they are just stored as files.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] The number and variety of different data processes and storage locations can become overwhelming for users.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] This inspired the usage of a workflow management system (e.g.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Airflow) to allow the data tasks to be specified, created, and monitored.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] The tasks are often specified as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Business objectives that executives set for what's to come are characterized in key business plans, with their more noteworthy definition in tactical business plans and implementation in operational business plans.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Most businesses today recognize the fundamental need to grow a business plan that follows this strategy.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] It is often difficult to implement these plans because of the lack of transparency at the tactical and operational degrees of organizations.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] This kind of planning requires feedback to allow for early correction of problems that are due to miscommunication and misinterpretation of the business plan.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] The design of data systems involves several components such as architecting data platforms, and designing data stores.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Data modeling is the process of producing a data model, an abstract model to describe the data and relationships between different parts of the data.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] A **data engineer** is a type of software engineer who creates big data ETL pipelines to manage the flow of data through the organization.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] This makes it possible to take huge amounts of data and translate it into insights.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] They are focused on the production readiness of data and things like formats, resilience, scaling, and security.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] Data engineers usually hail from a software engineering background and are proficient in programming languages like Java, Python, Scala, and Rust.
[src:data-mesh/data-engineering] They will be more familiar with databases, architecture, cloud computing, and Agile software development.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Data governance involves delegating authority over data and exercising that authority through decision-making processes.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] It plays a role in enhancing the value of data assets.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Data governance at the macro level involves regulating cross-border data flows among countries, which is more precisely termed *international data governance*.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] There have been several international groups established by research organizations that aim to grant access to their data.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] These groups that enable an exchange of data are, as a result, exposed to domestic and international legal interpretations that ultimately decide how data is used.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] However, as of 2023, there are no international laws or agreements specifically focused on data protection.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Data governance is the set of principles, policies, and processes that guide the effective and responsible use of data within an organization.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] It creates a framework for decision making, accountability, and oversight across the data lifecycle, from creation and storage to sharing and disposal.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Data governance is closely linked with data management, which provides the practical methods to carry out governance objectives.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] These methods include data quality assurance, metadata management, master data management, security controls, and compliance monitoring.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Together, governance and management aim to maximize the value of data as a strategic asset, reduce risks from misuse or inaccuracy, and ensure compliance with regulatory, ethical, and business requirements.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] The importance of this discipline has grown with the rise of big data, cloud computing, and artificial intelligence, where consistent standards and stewardship are essential for privacy protection, interoperability, and informed decision making.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] In 2010, they published a data governance framework based on five components: data principles (which define the data's purpose by an organization), data quality, metadata, data access, and data lifecycle.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] In 2017, the ISO released a framework for data governance, ISO/IEC 38505-1:2017.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Due to the increased use of large language models and the datasets used to train them, a 2022 paper proposed a data governance framework in the context of human rights.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Other well-known data governance frameworks include ISO 8000, the CMMI Data Management Maturity (DMM) Model, and DAMA-DMBOK.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] While data governance initiatives can be driven by a desire to improve data quality, they are often driven by C-level leaders responding to external regulations.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] In a recent report conducted by the CIO WaterCooler community, 54% stated the key driver was efficiencies in processes; 39% - regulatory requirements; and only 7% customer service.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Examples of these regulations include Sarbanes–Oxley Act, Basel I, Basel II, HIPAA, GDPR, cGMP, and a number of data privacy regulations.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] To achieve compliance with these regulations, business processes and controls require formal management processes to govern the data subject to these regulations.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Successful programs identify drivers that are meaningful to both supervisory and executive leadership.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Common themes among the external regulations center on the need to manage risk.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] The risks can be financial misstatement, inadvertent release of sensitive data, or poor data quality for key decisions.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Methods to manage these risks vary from industry to industry.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Examples of commonly referenced best practices and guidelines include COBIT, ISO/IEC 38500, and others.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] The proliferation of regulations and standards creates challenges for data governance professionals, particularly when multiple regulations overlap the data being managed.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Organizations often launch data governance initiatives to address these challenges.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Data governance initiatives improve the quality of data by assigning a team responsible for data's accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, validity, and uniqueness.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] This team usually consists of executive leadership, project management, line-of-business managers, and data stewards.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] The team usually employs a methodology for tracking and improving enterprise data, such as Six Sigma, and tools for data mapping, profiling, cleansing, and monitoring data.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Many data governance initiatives are also inspired by past attempts to fix information quality at the departmental level, which can lead to incongruent and redundant data quality processes.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Most large companies have many applications and databases that can not easily share information.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Therefore, knowledge workers within large organizations may not have access to the data they need to best do their jobs.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] When they do have access to the data, the data quality may be poor.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] By setting up a data governance practice or corporate data authority (individual or area responsible for determining how to proceed, in the best interest of the business, when a data issue arises), these problems can be mitigated.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Implementation of a data governance initiative may vary in scope as well as origin.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Sometimes, an executive mandate will arise to initiate an enterprise-wide effort.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Sometimes the mandate will be to create a pilot project or projects, limited in scope and objectives, aimed at either resolving existing issues or demonstrating value.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Sometimes, an initiative originates from lower down in the organization's hierarchy and will be deployed in a limited scope to demonstrate value to potential sponsors higher up in the organization.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] The initial scope of an implementation can vary greatly as well, from review of a one-off IT system to a cross-organization initiative.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Leaders of successful data governance programs declared at the Data Governance Conference in Orlando, FL, in December 2006, that data governance is about 80 to 95 percent communication.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] That stated, it is a given that many of the objectives of a data governance program must be accomplished with appropriate tools.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Many vendors are now positioning their products as data governance tools.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Due to the different focus areas of various data governance initiatives, a given tool may or may not be appropriate.
[src:data-mesh/data-governance] Additionally, many tools that are not marketed as governance tools address governance needs and demands.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:data-mesh/data-lakehouse] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Thus each team share and manage its own separate data product separately instead of relying on one central data team.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] The organization provides common tools, governance and standards so other teams can easily access or use the required data.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] The term *data mesh* was first defined by Zhamak Dehghani in 2019 while she was working as a principal consultant at the technology company Thoughtworks.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Dehghani introduced the term in 2019 and then provided greater detail on its principles and logical architecture throughout 2020.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] The process was predicted to be a “big contender” for companies in 2022.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Data meshes have been implemented by companies such as Zalando, Netflix, Intuit, VistaPrint, PayPal and others.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] In 2022, Dehghani left Thoughtworks to found Nextdata Technologies to focus on decentralized data.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] In addition to these principles, Dehghani writes that the data products created by each domain team should be discoverable, addressable, trustworthy, possess self-describing semantics and syntax, be interoperable, secure, and governed by global standards and access controls.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] In other words, the data should be treated as a product that is ready to use and reliable.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] After its introduction in 2019 multiple companies started to implement a data mesh and share their experiences.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Companies report difficulties to adopt a federated governance structure for activities and processes that were previously centrally owned and enforced.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] This is especially true for security, privacy, and regulatory topics.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] In data mesh individuals within domains are end-to-end responsible for data products.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] This new responsibility can be challenging, because it is rarely compensated and usually benefits other domains.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Research has shown a severe lack of comprehension for the data mesh paradigm among employees of companies implementing a data mesh.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Addressing C1, organizations should introduce a cross-domain steering unit responsible for strategic planning, use case prioritization, and the enforcement of specific governance rules—especially concerning security, regulatory, and privacy-related topics.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Nevertheless, a cross-domain steering unit can only complement and support the federated governance structure and may grow obsolete with the increasing maturity of the data mesh.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Addressing C2., organizations should observe and score data product quality as tracking and ranking key data products can encourage high-quality offerings, motivate domain owners, and support budget negotiations.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Organizations should thoroughly assess and evaluate their existing data systems, consider organizational factors, and weigh the potential benefits before implementing a data mesh.
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] When introducing data mesh, it is advised to carefully and consciously introduce data mesh terminology to ensure a clear understanding of the concept (C3).
[src:data-mesh/data-mesh] Scott Hirleman has started a data mesh community that contains over 7,500 people in their Slack channel.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Under domain-driven design, the structure and language of software code (class names, class methods, class variables) should match the business domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] For example: if software processes loan applications, it might have classes like "loan application", "customers", and methods such as "accept offer" and "withdraw".
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Critics of domain-driven design argue that developers must typically implement a great deal of isolation and encapsulation to maintain the model as a pure and helpful construct.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] While domain-driven design provides benefits such as maintainability, Microsoft recommends it only for complex domains where the model provides clear benefits in formulating a common understanding of the domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The term was coined by Eric Evans in his book of the same name published in 2003.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design articulates a number of high-level concepts and practices.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Of primary importance is a *domain* of the software, the subject area to which the user applies a program.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Software's developers build a *domain model*: a system of abstractions that describes selected aspects of a domain and can be used to solve problems related to that domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] These aspects of domain-driven design aim to foster a *common language* shared by domain experts, users, and developers—the *ubiquitous language*.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The ubiquitous language is used in the domain model and for describing system requirements.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Ubiquitous language is one of the pillars of DDD together with *strategic design* and *tactical design*.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In domain-driven design, the domain layer is one of the common layers in an object-oriented multilayered architecture.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design recognizes multiple kinds of models.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] For example, an *entity* is an object defined not by its attributes, but its identity.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] As an example, most airlines assign a unique number to seats on every flight: this is the seat's identity.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In contrast, a *value object* is an immutable object that contains attributes but has no conceptual identity.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] When people exchange business cards, for instance, they only care about the information on the card (its attributes) rather than trying to distinguish between each unique card.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Models can also define *events* (something that happened in the past).
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] A domain event is an event that domain experts care about.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Models can be bound together by a root entity to become an *aggregate*.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Objects outside the aggregate are allowed to hold references to the root but not to any other object of the aggregate.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The aggregate root checks the consistency of changes in the aggregate.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Drivers do not have to individually control each wheel of a car, for instance: they simply drive the car.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In this context, a car is an aggregate of several other objects (the engine, the brakes, the headlights, etc.).
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In domain-driven design, an object's creation is often separated from the object itself.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] A *repository*, for instance, is an object with methods for retrieving domain objects from a data store (e.g. a database).
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Similarly, a factory is an object with methods for directly creating domain objects.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] When part of a program's functionality does not conceptually belong to any object, it is typically expressed as a service.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] There are different types of events in DDD, and opinions on their classification may vary.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain events signify important occurrences within a specific business domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] These events are restricted to a bounded context and are vital for preserving business logic.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Typically, domain events have lighter payloads, containing only the necessary information for processing.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] This is because event listeners are generally within the same service, where their requirements are more clearly understood.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] On the other hand, integration events serve to communicate changes across different bounded contexts.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] They are crucial for ensuring data consistency throughout the entire system.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Integration events tend to have more complex payloads with additional attributes, as the needs of potential listeners can differ significantly.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] This often leads to a more thorough approach to communication, resulting in overcommunication to ensure that all relevant information is effectively shared.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Context Mapping identifies and defines the boundaries of different domains or subdomains within a larger system.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] It helps visualize how these contexts interact and relate to each other.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Although domain-driven design is not inherently tied to object-oriented approaches, in practice, it exploits the advantages of such techniques.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] These include entities/aggregate roots as receivers of commands/method invocations, the encapsulation of state within foremost aggregate roots, and on a higher architectural level, bounded contexts.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] As a result, domain-driven design is often associated with Plain Old Java Objects and Plain Old CLR Objects, which are technical implementation details, specific to Java and the .NET Framework respectively.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] These terms reflect a growing view that domain objects should be defined purely by the business behavior of the domain, rather than by a more specific technology framework.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Similarly, the naked objects pattern holds that the user interface can simply be a reflection of a good enough domain model.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Requiring the user interface to be a direct reflection of the domain model will force the design of a better domain model.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design has influenced other approaches to software development.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain-specific modeling, for instance, is domain-driven design applied with domain-specific languages.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Domain-driven design does not specifically require the use of a domain-specific language, though it could be used to help define a domain-specific language and support domain-specific multimodeling.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In turn, aspect-oriented programming makes it easy to factor out technical concerns (such as security, transaction management, logging) from a domain model, letting them focus purely on the business logic.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] While domain-driven design is compatible with model-driven engineering and model-driven architecture, the intent behind the two concepts is different.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Model-driven architecture is more concerned with translating a model into code for different technology platforms than defining better domain models.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] However, the techniques provided by model-driven engineering (to model domains, to create domain-specific languages to facilitate the communication between domain experts and developers,...) facilitate domain-driven design in practice and help practitioners get more out of their models.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Thanks to model-driven engineering's model transformation and code generation techniques, the domain model can be used to generate the actual software system that will manage it.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Command Query Responsibility Segregation (CQRS) is an architectural pattern for separating reading data (a 'query') from writing to data (a 'command').
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] CQRS derives from Command and Query Separation (CQS), coined by Bertrand Meyer.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Commands mutate state and are approximately equivalent to method invocation on aggregate roots or entities.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Queries read state but do not mutate it.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] While CQRS does not require domain-driven design, it makes the distinction between commands and queries explicit with the concept of an aggregate root.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The idea is that a given aggregate root has a method that corresponds to a command and a command handler invokes the method on the aggregate root.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The aggregate root is responsible for performing the logic of the operation and either yielding a failure response or just mutating its own state that can be written to a data store.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The command handler pulls in infrastructure concerns related to saving the aggregate root's state and creating needed contexts (e.g., transactions).
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Event storming is a collaborative, workshop-based modeling technique which can be used as a precursor in the context of Domain-Driven Design (DDD) to identify and understand domain events.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] This interactive discovery process involves stakeholders, domain experts, and developers working together to visualize the flow of domain events, their causes, and their effects, fostering a shared understanding of the domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The technique often uses color-coded sticky notes to represent different elements, such as domain events, aggregates, and external systems, facilitating a clear and structured exploration of the domain.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Event storming can aid in discovering subdomains, bounded contexts, and aggregate boundaries, which are key constructs in DDD.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] By focusing on 'what happens' in the domain, the technique can help uncover business processes, dependencies, and interactions, providing a foundation for implementing DDD principles and aligning system design with business goals.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Event sourcing is an architectural pattern in which entities track their internal state not by means of direct serialization or object-relational mapping, but by reading and committing events to an event store.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] When event sourcing is combined with CQRS and domain-driven design, aggregate roots are responsible for validating and applying commands (often by having their instance methods invoked from a Command Handler), and then publishing events.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] This is also the foundation upon which the aggregate roots base their logic for dealing with method invocations.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Hence, the input is a command and the output is one or many events which are saved to an event store, and then often published on a message broker for those interested (such as an application's view).
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Modeling aggregate roots to output events can isolate internal state even further than when projecting read-data from entities, as in standard *n*-tier data-passing architectures.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] One significant benefit is that axiomatic theorem provers (e.g.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Microsoft Contracts and CHESS) are easier to apply, as the aggregate root comprehensively hides its internal state.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] Events are often persisted based on the version of the aggregate root instance, which yields a domain model that synchronizes in distributed systems through optimistic concurrency.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in Domain-Driven Design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:data-mesh/domain-driven-design] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
